<div id="review_4169902185" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4169902185" />
    <a title="Dylan Siebert" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/120228419-dylan-siebert"><img alt="Dylan Siebert" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606074982p2/120228419.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4169902185?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Dylan Siebert" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Dylan Siebert" href="/user/show/120228419-dylan-siebert">Dylan Siebert</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4169902185" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2563814154881017246">I&apos;ve read this book four or five times now. I return to it when I want to be with characters for whom affection and trust are as real as the danger and cruelty all around them. These four linked novellas are stories of people finding each other, and though they take place on distant planets, the people in them are all as human as you and me.<br/><br/>Yeowe is a colony world shaped by the labour of slaves, and its long struggle for liberation and independence has finally been won. Werel, the world of the c</span>
  <span id="freeText2563814154881017246" style="display:none">I've read this book four or five times now. I return to it when I want to be with characters for whom affection and trust are as real as the danger and cruelty all around them. These four linked novellas are stories of people finding each other, and though they take place on distant planets, the people in them are all as human as you and me.<br /><br />Yeowe is a colony world shaped by the labour of slaves, and its long struggle for liberation and independence has finally been won. Werel, the world of the colonizers, is feeling the first tremors of change as slaves and masters alike awaken to the possibility of a world of equals. In the midst of all this are newly-arrived ambassadors of the Ekumen, a consortium of human-inhabited planets whose mission is learning and fellowship and non-interference (well, mostly) between worlds.<br /><br />The people of Werel and Yeowe are as vivid as they are varied. Yoss is an old woman trying to let go of a painful past; Solly is an interplanetary diplomat; Teyeo is a soldier. Havzhiva grew up in a village, but crossed the gulf between stars in search of a home. Rakam was born a slave, but lives to fight for the liberation of women in a strange new world. Esdan is the kind of man who pulls strings, until he finds himself pulled into danger and vulnerability as the tides of revolution rise.<br /><br />The first of the four novellas, 'Betrayals,' is slow, but it paints a portrait in miniature of the two worlds in conflict. The second, 'Forgiveness Day,' is my personal favourite. The third and fourth, 'A Man of the People' and 'A Woman's Liberation,' complete each other in beautiful and surprising ways. If you can get hold of a copy of The Collected Stories and Novellas of Ursula K. Le Guin, as I did, you'll also be able to read the brilliant fifth novella, unpublished in the original edition: 'Old Music and the Slave Women'.<br /><br />A wonderful, wonderful book, all the more so because much of what it has to say is so softly spoken. In the midst of crisis and upheaval, there are moments of beauty and intimacy, but it takes an eye and a pen like Le Guin's to see them and to write them.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2563814154881017246" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

